<LegalLayout
  title="Billing Flags & Confidence Levels"
  description="How PatientBillGuide detects possible billing concerns and reports confidence."
  crumbs={[
    { label: 'Methodology', href: '/methodology/' },
    { label: 'Billing Flags' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    When bill review tools launch, each finding will include a <strong>confidence level</strong> and
    plain-English explanation. We never label something as fraud without evidence — we surface
    patterns worth asking about.
  </p>

  <h2>Flag types (planned)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Duplicate charge</strong> — same procedure code, date, and similar amount appears
      more than once
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>NCCI bundle concern</strong> — two procedure codes on the same date that CMS often
      considers bundled under National Correct Coding Initiative edits
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Price above benchmark</strong> — charged amount far above Medicare allowed for that
      code and locality
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Modifier review</strong> — modifier combinations that may need clarification from the
      billing office
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Confidence levels</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High</strong> — strong pattern match on public rules (e.g. exact duplicate line)</li>
    <li><strong>Medium</strong> — plausible concern; documentation or contract context may explain it</li>
    <li><strong>Low</strong> — informational; common in some settings (e.g. above Medicare but within commercial range)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>“Bill looks normal” is a valid result</h2>
  <p>
    Many bills pass automated checks. We will say so clearly when no flags are found — that is not a
    guarantee of accuracy, but it means our public-data rules did not surface a common concern.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a href="/methodology/limitations/">Read known limitations →</a>
  </p>
</LegalLayout>
